text: Hmm... looks rather promising. Yeah it could end up having some typical biopic film traits but Chadwick Boseman seems to be doing a good job at mimicking Brown's movements and his voice. This seems like a massive step up from 42 where he was just... okay.   Though I am still wondering what the actual plot is. Outside of course the rise of James Brown and the impact he had on pop-culture and music. Just based off the trailer, it seems to have a lot of the troupes that are in every biopic. Troubled childhood and young adult years, rise to fame, doing something that isn't "the norm", but in the end it gains him great success and so on.   I don't think this is going to be the next "Ray", but this could also be just a nice little film to show a little more of who he was and maybe help expose more people to his music.   I'll give it a shot.

text: went to see Ray and Whats love got to do with it on opening day. both movies delved into enough of what shaped the protagonists and the relationships that molded them.  the acting was undeniable and the music that made them famous only added to the thrill of it all.  Besides that, the storyline kept you interested and forced you to care about what was going to happen next to these people.  movies like get on up, why do fools fall in love (about Frankie lymon) and a couple of others did the opposite for me.  10 minutes in I knew I wouldn't be satisfied and would have no desire to revisit as I have Ray & Whats love.   The lead actor  in get on up did fine and the music made you want to jump out of your seat & dance but the storyline was choppy, lacked in the area of relationship building or really caring one way or the other about what was going to happen.. it' was like a bunch of scenes thrown together to make an abstract movie with a sound track as its backdrop.  if you know anything about james or not, you can follow it but again, 10 minutes in you almost don't care. I don't get the feeling that the creators cared much about a great story line, but more so being the first to throw out a biopic about Mr Brown.  They were probably hoping to get similar results as ray.  not going to happen & if it does it will be undeserving. Fans of Mr Brown will like it because of the music & the guy who does the role justice but I can't see any other reason than that and I can't see it doing as well as Ray.  word of mouth sometimes  is everything.

text: Hope they don't show the dancing in quick cuts. You know. Like those martial arts movies where they do all those quick cuts and 30 different angles of the same move to make you think they're moving real fast. When you see Brown, Jackson and Lee (Bruce) you get a long continuous shot (which Bruce Lee insisted upon) to let you know there is no splicing; it's all them. When you see those fast edits you know someone messed up. So now they have to show part of the move, fix it and quick cut from where they messed up.  Seems like they focused on how JB sounded rather than his moves in the trailer. In fact I didn't see any of James Browns trademark moves. Maybe Trailer #2 is better.

text: I really enjoyed the movie and the lead actor did a good job in portraying James Brown. Seeing the film made me want to go and research not James Brown, but Bobby Byrd and how they really met. It was interesting reading just to find out how much of an influence Bobby Byrd actually had in the recordings of James Brown. Read about Bobby Byrd on Waikaepaedia and get the real truth. James Brown had the stage presence, that it persona but if not for Bobby Bryd not only discovering James, but being the influence behind most of his hits (without the recognition), we may never have heard of James Brown; one interesting note I found out was that the Gospel Starlighters actually changed their name to The Flames prior to James joining the group and it also tells how they actually met. I realize movies take liberties to change facts around, but it makes me want to see just how close the movie was to the truth, never the less, a really enjoyable movie. If Jamie can get an Oscar for his portrayal of Ray, why not Chad; a performance filled with a lot of energy in my opinion. In closing, check out the story of Bobby Bryd.

text: I think they wouldn’t do one about MJ because he was pretty fragile. I was obsessed with Michael Jackson recently and I watched and read everything about him I could find. And according to those things his life wasn’t beautiful at all it was pretty painful. He was lonely when I say lonely it REALLY LONELY! No friends, no family. Only bodyguards, accountants, managers, paparazzi. He couldn’t enjoy things like other people. I can’t even explain. This guy’s life was just way too painful. The fear, the paranoia,.. all of that just too sad. And the fact that on the outside you could never imagine what he was going through. On the outside it was all glam and glitters
